<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n03151a"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n03" href="#n03151a">N03 (VI.B.3)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n03all.htm#n03151a"> 151(a)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> eponymous</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">One day I met a handsome youth in his company named John Gray, and I could not wonder that Oscar found him interesting, for Gray had not only great personal distinction, but charming manners and a marked poetic gift, a much greater gift than Oscar possessed. He had besides an eager, curious mind, and of course found extraordinary stimulus in Oscar&apos;s talk. It seemed to me that intellectual sympathy and the natural admiration which a younger man feels for a brilliant senior formed the obvious bond between them. But no sooner did Oscar republish &ldquo;Dorian Gray&rdquo; than ill-informed and worse-minded persons went about saying that the <mark>eponymous</mark> hero of the book was John Gray, though &ldquo;Dorian Gray&rdquo; was written before Oscar had met or heard of John Gray. <small> Frank Harris, <a name="FHOW2" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#FHOW2"><cite title="source">Oscar Wilde His Life and Confessions</cite></a> (1918) 63</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
